ives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ednywain Ap Eginir was born about 1090, in Powys, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Eginier ap Gollwyn, was 37 and his mother, Mrs Eginir Gollwyn, was 27. He married Mrs Ednywain Ap Eginir about 1130, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1090–":"umbes 1090–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1132–1215":"1132–1215","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1054–1094":"1054–1094","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1090":"1090","about 1090":"umbes 1090",